'''Atâ-Malek Juvayni''' (1226&ndash;1283) ({{lang-fa|عطاملک جوینی}}), in full, Ala al-Din Ata-ullah ({{lang-fa|علاءالدین عطاءالله}}), was a [[Persian people|Persian]] historian who wrote an account of the [[Mongol Empire]] entitled ''[[Tarikh-i Jahangushay-i Juvaini|Tarīkh-i Jahān-gushā]]'' (''History of the World Conqueror'').
He was born in Juvayn, a city in [[Greater Khorasan|Khorasan]] in eastern [[Persia]]. Both his grandfather and his father, Baha al-Din, had held the post of ''sahib-divan'' or Minister of Finance for [[Mingburnu|Muhammad Jalal al-Din]] and [[Ögedei Khan]] respectively. Baha al-Din also acted as deputy c. 1246 for his immediate superior, the emir Arghun<!-- This is not Arghun Khan but someone else. -->, in which role he oversaw a large area including [[Kingdom of Georgia]].
Juvayni too became an important official of the empire. He visited the Mongol capital of [[Karakorum]] twice, beginning his history of the Mongols conquests on one such visit (c. 1252-53). He was with [[Hulagu Khan|Ilkhan Hulagu]] in 1256 at the taking of [[Alamut]] and was responsible for saving part of its celebrated library. He had also accompanied Hulagu during the [[sack of Baghdad]] in 1258, and the next year was appointed governor of [[Baghdad]], Lower [[Mesopotamia]], and [[Khuzistan]]. Around 1282, Juvayni attended a Mongol ''[[Kurultai|quriltai]],'' or assembly, held in the Ala-Taq pastures northeast of [[Lake Van]]. He died the following year in [[Mughan]] or [[Arran (Caucasus)|Arran]] in [[Azerbaijan (Iran)|Azerbaijan]].
Juvayni's brother was the powerful [[Shams al-Din Juvayni|Shams al-Din Mohammad Sahib-Divan]], who had served as Minister of Finance under Hulagu and [[Abaqa Khan]]. A skillful leader in his own right, Shams al-Din also had influential in-laws: his wife Khoshak was the daughter of [[Avag Mkhargrdzeli]], [[Amirspasalar|Lord High Constable]] of Georgia, and [[Gvantsa Kakhaberidze|Gvantsa]], a noblewoman who went on to become [[List of monarchs of Georgia|queen of Georgia]].
Juvayni's own position at court and his family connections made him privy to information unavailable to other historians. For unknown reasons Juvayni's history terminates in 1260, more than twenty years before his death.
The standard edition of Juvayni's history is published under the title ''Tarīkh-i Jahān-gushā'', ed. [[Mohammad Ghazvini|Mirza Muhammad Qazwini]], 3 vol, Gibb Memorial Series 16 (Leiden and London, 1912–37). An English translation by John Andrew Boyle ''The History of the World-Conqueror'' was republished in 1997.
