'''Barry Selwyn Gustafson''' (born 1938) is a New Zealand [[political scientist]] and [[historian]], and a leading political biographer.  He served for nearly four decades as Professor of [[Political Studies]] at the [[University of Auckland]], and as Acting Director of the [[New Zealand Asia Institute]] from 2004 to 2006. He has contested various [[Elections in New Zealand|general election]]s, first for the [[New Zealand Labour Party|Labour Party]] and later for the [[New Zealand National Party|National Party]], coming second each time.

==Early life==
Barry Selwyn Gustafson was born in Auckland in 1938.  He was educated at Auckland, [[Massey University|Massey]] and [[Glasgow University|Glasgow]] Universities (BA 1960, MA 1962, PhD 1974).{{sfn|Gustafson|1986|loc=dust-jacket}}

==Politics and academia==
He was a member of the Labour Party from 1954 to 1981, and stood in two general elections as a candidate; in {{NZ election link year|1960}} and in {{NZ election link year|1966}}. In 1960, he contested the "blue-ribbon" {{NZ electorate link|Remuera}} electorate and lost by 6109 votes to National's [[Ronald Algie]]. In 1966, he contested the {{NZ electorate link|Taupo}} electorate and narrowly lost by 258 votes by National's [[Rona Stevenson]]. He wrote that National was afraid of losing the seat so poured ''thousands of dollars'' into the campaign. A hundred Waikato women canvassed every house in Tokoroa and Putaruru over two days, using the ''street lists and blue dot system''.{{sfn|Gustafson|1986|pp=91,280}}

In 1968 he joined the staff at Auckland University, and during his long tenure at Auckland he has authored several leading books on the topic of New Zealand politics.  He wrote ''Social Change and Party Reorganisation'' (1976) and ''Labour’s Path to Political Independence'' (1980) while still a Labour Party member, but after completing ''The First 50 Years: A History of the New Zealand National Party'' (1986) changed allegiance to National. In 1986 he also published ''From the Cradle to the Grave: A Biography of [[Michael Joseph Savage]]''.

In [[New Zealand general election, 1987|1987]] he stood as a National candidate for the [[Birkenhead (New Zealand electorate)|Birkenhead electorate]] to replace the retiring [[Jim McLay]], but was defeated by the [[New Zealand Labour Party|Labour]] candidate, [[Jenny Kirk (politician)|Jenny Kirk]].

During the 1990s Gustafson was given a number of international academic appointments, including visiting researcher at Stanford University and the European Union in 1990, and research at a number of [[United States|American]] and [[United Kingdom|British]] Universities in 1994.  In 1997 Gustafson was [[Fulbright Program|Fulbright Visiting Professor]] at [[Georgetown University]].  From 1998 to 2002 Gustafson was appointed Head of the Political Studies Department, and he was also Pro [[Vice-Chancellor]] (International) of the University from 2001 to 2002.  In 2000 he published ''His Way: A Biography of [[Robert Muldoon]]''.

Gustafson's teaching interests are predominantly the [[European Union]], [[civil society]], the development of New Zealand’s political culture and parties, political leadership and power, and [[interdisciplinary studies]]. For 25 years he also taught [[Soviet Studies|Soviet]] and [[East European Studies]].

In 2004 Gustafson retired as Professor of Political Studies, and was appointed Acting Director of the New Zealand Asia Institute, a position he held until 2006.  In this time he helped to establish a [[New Zealand Studies]] Centre at [[Peking University]].  In 2007 he published ''Kiwi Keith: A Biography of [[Keith Holyoake]]''.

