{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> | name = José Corona Núnez | image = José Corona Núnez.jpg <!--Please see the talk page before making any changes to the portrait--> | image_size = | caption = Photograph of José Corona Nunéz in December 1994 in his house in Morelia, Michoacán, México | birth_date = {{Birth date|1906|07|04|df=y}} <!-- Please don't change it to 23 April. See the section below on Early Life. --> | birth_place = [[Cuitzeo]], [[Michoacan]], [[Mexico]]. | death_date = {{Death date and age|2002|01|02|1906|07|04|df=y}} | death_place = Morelia, Michoacan, Mexico | spouse = {{marriage| Maria Ramirez 21st June 1914-27 September 2014}} | children = {{unbulleted list|Araceli Corona Ramirez 1931-2016, Rene Juan Corona Ramirez 1933-2008, Cuitzeman Corona Ramirez 1940-/}} | occupation = Anthropologist, Historian, Professor}}
'''José Corona Núñez''' (July 4, 1906 – January 6, 2002) was a Mexican author, anthropologist, and history professor who discovered several important archeological sites throughout [[Mexico|México]]. His main body of work revolved around his native state of [[Michoacán]], and in particular the Tarascan or [[Purépecha people|Purépecha]] culture.
== Early life == José Corona Núñez was born in [[Cuitzeo|Cuitzeo del Porvenir]] on July 4, 1906. His father was Marcelino Corona García and his mother was María del Pilar Núñez Berrospe. From an early age he attended the Agustino Convent of [[Cuitzeo]] and helped with the various common rituals.
== Education and religious studies == Through his involvement with the convent Corona Núñez decided to pursuit priesthood. He would later clarify that his primary motivation was to continue to learn and given his family's limited resources private schooling was not an option. In January 1920 he began his seminary studies in the San Pablo Convent of [[Yuriria]], Guanajuato. There he studied Latin, Greek, French, Grammar, Religion, and Mexican history, amongst other topics. He then moved to another convent in [[San Luis Potosí]] to continue his studies as a [[Hermit]] and continue his studies. On October 2, 1923, at the age of 17, he became Friar Angel in the [[Order of Saint Augustine]]. However, the following year he resigned by mailing a letter to the Prior General in Rome asking for his removal. The last religious ceremony in which he participated took place in his native convent of [[Cuitzeo]] in which he was disrobed and he removed all emblems (belt, cross, etc.) and signed a document addressed to the [[Holy See|Vatican]] declaring the acknowledgement of his request, on April 5, 1926.
== Career == Corona Núñez received a scholarship to attend the [[National School of Anthropology and History]] ("Escuela Nacional de Antropología e Historia"). As a student he worked with [https://www.britannica.com/contributor/Donald-Dilworth-Brand/355 Donald D. Brand] in his work "Quiroga, A Mexican Municipio".<ref>{{cite book |url=http://amzn.com/125862589X |title=Quiroga: A Mexican Municipio |author=Donald Dilworth Brand |isbn=9781258625894 |website=Amzn.com |date= |accessdate=2016-03-31}}</ref> After his studies he became a rural teacher and eventually director of various primary schools throughout [[Michoacan]]. He later became Director of the Anthropology Department of the State of [[Nayarit]], founded the Anthropology Museums of Tepic and Colima, and was in charge of the Anthropology Department of the [[Universidad Michoacana de San Nicolás de Hidalgo|University of Michoacan]].
As an anthropologist José Corona Núnez discovered the circular pyramid of the [[Ixtlán del Rio (archaeological site)|Ixtlán del Rio]] archeological site.
== Bibliography == José Corona Núnez created more than 100 articles and published more than a dozen books <ref>[https://www.google.com/search?tbo=p&tbm=bks&q=inauthor:%22Jos%C3%A9+Corona+N%C3%BA%C3%B1ez%22] {{dead link|date=March 2016}}</ref> throughout the 20th century. Some of the more well known are: * Mitologia Tarasca (1957, Fondo de Cultura Económica) * Historia de los Antiguos Habitantes de Michoacán (1988, Balsar Editores SA de CV.<ref>{{cite book|author=Jose Corona Nunez |url=https://www.amazon.com/Historia-los-antiguos-habitantes-Michoacan/dp/9686009337 |title=Historia de los antiguos habitantes de Michoacan: Desde su origen hasta la conquista espanola (Spanish Edition): |isbn=9789686009330 |website=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=2016-03-31}}</ref>) * Voces del Pasado (1995, Centro de Estudios Cultura Nicolaita <ref>{{cite book|title=Voces del pasado: antologнa : cuentos, leyendas, estudios etno-histуricos |isbn=968-7376-32-5|date= }}</ref>) * Diccionario Geográfico Tarasco-Náhuatl (1993, UMSNH) * Curácuaro de Morelos (1991, Centro de Estudios Cultura Nicolaita)
