{{Chinese name|[[Tan (surname)|Tan]]}}

'''Tan Tai Yong''' ({{zh|c=陳大榮|p=Chén Dàróng}})) is a Professor of Humanities (History) at [[Yale-NUS College]], Professor of South Asian history at the [[National University of Singapore]] (NUS), and current President at [[Yale-NUS College]]. He is also Director of the [[Institute of South Asian Studies]], an autonomous university-level research institute in NUS.<ref>[http://www.nus.edu.sg/aboutus/management/tytan.php Home] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110120052220/http://www.nus.edu.sg/aboutus/management/tytan.php |date=2011-01-20 }}</ref> He previously served as Executive Vice-President (Academic Affairs) of Yale-NUS, Vice Provost (Student Life) at NUS, and Dean of [[Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences, National University of Singapore|Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences, NUS]]. Tan was also a former [[Nominated Member of Parliament]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Yale-NUS picks Tan Tai Yong as new president|url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/yale-nus-picks-tan-tai-yong-new-president|accessdate=2017-08-15|publisher=Channel News Asia|date=2017-03-14}}</ref>

== Biography ==
Professor Tan obtained his first two degrees - BA (Hons), 1986, and MA, 1989 - from the National University of Singapore. He then went off to [[Cambridge University]], where he earned his doctorate in South Asian history in 1992, under the supervision of [[Anthony Low]]. He has been a faculty member of the Department of History at NUS since 1992 and served the [[Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences]] as Sub-Dean (1994-1999), Head of the History Department (2000-2003), Vice-Dean (2001-2003) and Dean (2004-2009).

== Research ==
Professor Tan's research interests are in the areas of [[Sikh]] diaspora, civil-military relations, social and political history of colonial [[Punjab region|Punjab]], and the partition of South Asia. Lately, he has shifted his attention to [[Southeast Asia]], and has been exploring issues of networks formation and the place of maritime cities in the region.

